title: sekihan_(tradition)
body:
赤飯 ([i]sekihan[/i], literally, red rice) is a mixture of glutinous [[rice]] and azuki beans that is steamed and eaten seasoned with sesame and salt. 
In Japan, it is customary to eat sekihan at any celebration. It is also widely canned as emergency rations due to its high nutritional value. 
Recipes and customs vary from region to region, with some regions having a tradition of eating sekihan after a misfortune, for example. 

At one time in Japan, a girl's first menstruation was celebrated by the entire family eating sekihan, often to the confusion of her younger siblings. 
Even now, after this custom has been abandoned, insinuation of a connection between the start of menstruation and sekihan sometimes appears manga as a running gag. In some cases ”the first menstruation” is replaced by ”the lost of virginity” to make things more funny. 

h4.See also 

* "Wikipedia article":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sekihan

title: relife
body:
ReLIFE

A very popular ongoing webcomic series by [[Yayoi Sou]] that serialized in Comico. It is the first series ever from Comico that was published as a tankoubon volume with the first volume published by Earth Star Comics on 12 August 2014. An anime adaption by TMS Entertainment has been announced for the Summer 2016 season.
 
The story follows [[Kaizaki Arata]], a 27 year old jobless man who fails at every job interviews he had after quitting his last company which he only last 3 months. His life changes after he met [[Yoake Ryou]] of the ReLife Research Institute, who offer him a drug that can change his appearance to 17 years old again and to became a subject in a 1-year experiment in which he begin his life as a high school student again.

title: provisional_plate
body: A type of vehicle plate, similar in appearance to an L-plate. Much like the [[shoshinsha mark]] in Japan, it's designed to show that the driver has completed their learner's qualifications, but they're still new to driving. In some countries such as [[Australia]], [[Malaysia]] and [[Hong Kong]], new drivers are legally required for a certain amount of time to display these plates on any vehicles they drive, while other countries such as the [[United Kingdom]] tend to recommend the use of these plates without actually making it mandatory.

body:
Children of the false city. Their duty is to be mourners. They are dress-up dolls that pretend to cry in order to liven up funeral processions. The dolls present are Haughtiness, Gloominess, Liar, Heartlessness, Selfishness, Slander, Folly, Jealousy, Sloth, Vanity, Cowardice, Stupidity, Prejudice, and Obstinacy. The last to arrive, Love, has yet to be seen.

Is an Brazillian webseries created by [[Ronaldo de Azevedo]] featuring the daily life of [[Cueio (character)|Cueio]] (Bunni), [[primo (cueio)|Primo]] (Cousin) and [[Vaco]] (Caw)

Cueio has forgot about your past, due to something which wasn't revealed. Now the characters are the way of the Tournament.

Cueio was released on 2013, November 7th. Since its inception got quite repercussions and sharing. Using YouTube, it is a series of short videos presenting simple characters, striking and charismatic, with humor and also a dash of drama and nostalgia. Easy to understand, the audience is not defined by age, since the message is open to all audiences. The channel reached the milestone of 1 million views at one year of its creation, on April 3, 2014 was in the 535,000 subscribers mark.

[[Cuguja]], [[Gulila]], [[Largato]], [[Cocodilo]], [[Lobi]], [[Pantela]] and [[Usso]] are other characters who have appeared in the series, and [[Tigui]] and [[Lendario Bovino]] (Legendary Bovine, Your Vaco).

title: aku_bouzu
body:
Aku-Bouzu, literally, "Ashy Baldhead" is a Japanese monster appearing in the folk lores/stories of the Tōhoku region, and is known by different names in some regions.
This monster lives in the [[ashes]] of a sunken hearth and leaps out at those who play around with the ash, drags them inside and eats them.
No folklore exists that tell of the appearance of an Aku-Bouzu. This is because it's one of the Japanese patterns of "bogeymen":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bogeyman].
Stories of Aku-Bouzu assaulting children who commit various acts considered "bad-manners" by adults ~such as bathing twice in a row on the same day, eating the food offered at the altar, going to the toilet naked~ also exist.

h4.See also

* "Wikipedia article (JP)":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E7%81%B0%E5%9D%8A%E4%B8%BB]

title: surechigai_fishing
body:
Surechigai Fishing, known as Ultimate Angler in North America and StreetPass Fishing in Europe/Australia, is a simulation game developed by Prope. The game is part of Surechigai Mii Hiroba, known as StreetPass Mii Plaza outside of Japan, for the Nintendo 3DS. In this game, players use bait received from encountered Miis to try and catch various species of fish across several islands.
